It looks like, when R runs the model through anova(), it takes the first parameter you give it, and calculates its SS from the empty model. Then, R creates a new regression line based on the first parameter, and estimates the SS of the second parameter based on this complex model, rather than the empty model. Since the 'slopes' of the complex models are quite different, the order in which R calculates SS will produce the large effect you see here.
